        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For emissivity parameter beta = 1.5 and the critical frequency nu0 = 2 THz, a grey body fit to the sub-mm data yields a total flux of 24.7 mJy at 349 GHz. This value depends on the grey body parameters very weakly. In order to distinguish between the subhalo model (SIE-ES-X-Y) and void model (SIE-ES-X-V), we need to measure the flux ratio C/(A1+A2+B) at 4.8 per cent accuracy (in green curve, figure 5). If the source size is negligible, the MIR flux ratios yield [table 3] 1.43 mJy for image C at 349 GHz. Then, we need to have sensitivity of 1.43*0.048/4=0.0172mJy for measuring the 4.8 per cent change in the flux ratio C/(A1+A2+B) if we require detection at 4 sigma level. Moreover, we can also measure the flux ratio C/B at &gt;5.8 sigma level as the flux change in C/B is more than 7 per cent (figure 5). If the source size is larger than 100 pc, the flux ratio C/(A1+A2+B) becomes larger by 10 percent to 50 per cent (figure 5). Then, the sub-mm flux of image C becomes also larger. Therefore, for extended sources, we can measure the 4.8 per cent change in C/(A1+A2+B) more accurately if we have sensitivity of 0.0176 mJy.  

With angular resolution 0.22 arcsec, the positions of the centroids of image B and C can be determined within an error of [beam size]/[S/N]=0.22/(1.43/0.0176)=0.0027 arcsec. This yields uncertainty of ~0.3 per cent in flux ratios, which is sufficiently smaller than the expected change due to the perturber (V or Y). If the source size L is larger than ~500pc, we cannot separate image B from A2 (see figure 4). However, we can still measure the distance between the boundary of C and that of A1. As shown in figure 4, the distance between C and A1 differs by &gt;0.3arcsec between the two models even if L is 800 pc. Therefore, we can still discriminate them.  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
